FIG. 1 is a perspective view showing a solid metal welding wire partially constructed in accordance with the present invention;


FIG. 2 is a partial cross-sectional area of the wire of FIG. 1;


FIG. 2A is the wire in FIG. 2 illustrating an outer metal sheath over the metal welding wire;


FIG. 2B is the wire in FIG. 2 with the indentations filled with a filling agent, and alloying agent and/or a fluxing agent;


FIG. 3 is a side elevational view schematically illustrating a procedure for forming the spaced quantized segments in the solid metal welding wire during the feeding of the wire by using two rotating forming wheels;


FIG. 3A is an enlarged cross sectional view taken generally along line 3A--3A of FIG. 3 at an indentation forming the bridging element;


FIG. 4 is a front perspective view schematically illustrating a procedure for forming the spaced quantized segments in the solid metal welding wire during the feeding of the wire by using two rotating forming wheels;


FIG. 5 is a composite view showing the coordination between current pulses in a pulse arc welding process and the mechanical aspects of the welding process explaining the relationship between the pulses and the quantized segments of a welding wire constructed in accordance with the present invention;


FIG. 6 is a schematic illustration of the welding process showing wire W passing through a contact sleeve as the wire W is melted at arc D by pulses as wire W is moved at a wire feed speed providing a quantized segment Q at the same time as a current pulse; and


FIG. 7 is a schematic illustration of the welding process showing the resistance through wire W as a function of the cross-sectional area of wire W.
